ASSIGNMENT #1 (Group):  Communication Covenant due January 11
 
A Communication Covenant is an agreement every member of a team makes about communicating: 
·  	promising to communicate regularly (even when the news is bad),
·  	promising to answer your email how many times a day,
·  	agreeing that you will be using Google Docs for file management,
·  	specifying when and where your meetings are (1-2 times a week),
·  	promising to notify team mates if you can’t make a meeting,
·  	agreeing to reasonable punishments if a team mate is late or misses without notifying everyone,
·  	promising to volunteer to do things and to do them well and on time. 
 
Include a table of preferred email addresses and cell phone numbers.  Title the file TEAMNAMEContacts
 
Put this file in the Google Docs folder your team is sharing with us.

Team Contract
Code of Conduct: As a project team we will:
-        Share the project workload and only commit to tasks that we feel we are capable of performing.
-        Anticipate potential problems and work to prevent them.
-        Keep other team members informed of information related to the project.
-        Strive to meet individual and team goals and deadlines.
-        Remain confidential with information regarding the project.
-        Focus on what is best for the team and the project as a whole.
-        See the entire project through to completion.
Participation:
-        Be honest and open during all meetings.
-        Be open to different ideas and approaches.
-        Everyone will have the opportunity to equally participate and will encourage the participation of other members.
-        Have one discussion at the time and try not to interrupt others.
-        Ensure that discussions are kept on track.
-        Let the team leader know in advance if a team member cannot attend a meeting for is having trouble meeting deadlines.
Communication:
-        Decide as a team the preferred method of communication. If team members cannot meet face-to-face, we will use other forms of communication such as telephone, videoconferencing, e-mail, and other forms of technology in order to inform each other of team meetings, announcements, updates, reminders, and problems.
-        Strive for open and direct communication with the rest of the team.
-        Share appropriate information with other team members.
-        Present all ideas clearly and concisely.
-        Listen effectively and show interest in what others are saying.
-        Ask questions if something is not understood.
Problem Solving:
-        Acknowledge all problems and identify them as specifically as possible.
-        Act as contributors to solving problems and look at the issue from various perspectives.
-        Only use constructive criticism to give feedback. Feedback will focus on solving problems and not on blaming others.
-        Be supportive rather than critical and combine and develop ideas until a solution is reached.
-        Strive to work together and build on each other’s ideas.
Decision Making:
-        Identify the decision that needs to be made.
-        Make decisions based on facts and data. If no data is available, gather whatever information is available.
-        Brainstorm, access, and discuss options.
-        Get input from all team members before a decision is reached.
-        Weigh the probabilities and discuss potential outcomes.
-        If concerns arise, discuss them openly and address them effectively to reach a common ground.
-        Ask all team members if they support a decision before the decision is made.
Handling Conflict:
-        Use this as an opportunity for growth and as a learning experience.
-        Listen openly to other points of view and be respectful of each other’s ideas.
-        Seek to understand other points of views, motivations, and goals before coming to conclusions.
-        Build on other team member’s ideas and valid points and brainstorm possible solutions.
-        Express your opinions assertively rather than aggressively.
-        Explore options together and be open to the idea that a third position may exist.
-        Seek to find some common ground for agreement.
Meeting Guidelines:
-        Plan to have face-to-face meetings every Monday and Wednesday night at 8:00 PM of every month. They will be held in the same place in SE 1304.
-        Emailed agendas will be issued 2 days in advanced by a designated team member, outlining issues that need to be addressed.
-        Meetings will being promptly and end of time. Cell phones will be turned off or put on silent.
-        The team leader will be responsible for facilitating the meeting and keeping the meeting on track.
-        Everyone will participate in meetings and come prepared.
-        Meeting minutes will be recorded and shared by a designated team member to all other team members within 24 hours. All meeting minutes will also be kept in Google Docs for referencing.
-        If a team member cannot attend a meeting, he/she must notify the rest of the team one day in advance or arrange for telephone or videoconferencing as needed.
-        Absent team members are responsible for contacting the rest of the team for meeting minutes.
Team Agreement Sign-off
-        I understand and agree to abide by this team contract to ensure the successful completion of the Gordias/Midas project.
-        Signatures:

There are some risks involved with this project. The biggest risk is that a website redesign may not change the visitor frequency at all and will fail at increasing APSA’s presence on campus. The new design could also possibly turn out even worse than the original design, unsuccessful in being more informative and visually appealing. Any changes made to the website holds the risk of possibly crashing the website, and in the worst scenario, deleting all information on the website and forcing a complete start from scratch. The club’s board and members could also show little interest in implementing a new redesign. The main business risk for this project is investing the necessary time and work into the project to complete the main objective of creating a website that improves APSA’s presence on campus.
